IN a few year’s time, preschool teachers will be yelling one
particular name to its little students.  This is because Mzansi’s most popular baby name is Enzokuhle
Dlamini,for the second year in a row. This interesting information was tweeted by Statistics South
earlier today among a variety of topics ranging from birth rates  unemployment.  Enzokuhle was the most popular baby name registered for boys
in 2017 and 2018 followed by Lethabo and Melokuhle. “These three were also the top three names for 2017 births,
and the order remained the same. For middle names, Junior was the most popular,
followed by Blessing and Gift.” Enzokuhle was also the 
most popular among baby girls registered followed by Melokuhle and then
Amahle since 2017. Enzokuhle and Melokuhle have similar meaning in Nguni ,both
meaning “they must do good things.” “For middle names amongst girls, the most popular choices
were Precious, Princess and Angel, in that order. Enzokuhle, Melokuhle, Omphile
and Amogelang were in the top ten list of names for both sexes. All the top ten
first names for both sexes were of native languages. Most of the popular baby
names for males and females reflect positive hopes for the child, express
beliefs or are inspired by positive connotations of both love and
acceptance”,said StatsSA. The most popular baby surnames is Dlamini, followed by Nkosi
and then Ndlovu. “It is interesting to note that nine of the surnames were
from the Nguni clans, namely isiZulu, isiXhosa, isiNdebele and siSwati. Mokoena
– which featured as the sixth most popular surname – was the only non-Nguni
surname”,added StatsSA. Just over 1 million births were registered in South Africa
in 2018, an increase of 2,0% from 2017 to 2018.